	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 08-22-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">08:32 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">I had known my friend Velena for some time and had always respected her abilities. She was one of the temples outstanding priests ... a bulwark of strength ... a pillar of truth ... and a true devotee to the path of rightousness. She set for us all a very high standard to be met. It was with this example that I had grown into my faith and into my chosen career path, that of a healer. <br />
<br />
However with the passing days I had heard rumors and tales of things that didn't seem right ... things said that were disturbing to me and my fellow adepts ... things that made us question our path. Things that were overheard at the dinner tables and in the halls of the temple ... things that were said in passing under their breath ... things that we were never meant to hear, certainly not by the likes of us. We had heard the elders and some of them seemed to be questioning their very own existance and they were questioning the future of the temple. It seemed as if several of them were about to throw it all away and give up the healing path. Without the teachers and scribes there would be no temple and with no temple there would be no adepts ... and before long ... no healers at all ... and then with no healers the heros would fall to their eventual end. Evil would win ... good would be vanquished. <br />
<br />
Well, I am no great hero but I got this into my head and I promised myself that I would make an effort to do what I could. So, I watched my mentor for a couple weeks and had noticed that she didn't venture out as much as she had once before, and she had seemed to become very disenfranchised in her own lot. She seemed meloncoly and looked to be at a junction in her life. Then one night at dinner I over heard her saying she was going to go out in the morning and might not be seen again ... I assumed that most thought she was taking on a dangerous mission for the temple. Being her squire, I knew she had no such mission and it set me to wondering what she was up to. I decided to follow her the next morning.<br />
<br />
It was with much antisapation that I geared up the next day with the thought of trailing her on this trip. As she had completely forgone the adventurers quest and settled for short jaunts and had refused to answer questions about where she was going and what she had been doing, I believed that this might very well be the last time we all saw her and was hoping to be able to help her or change her mind and prevent her from doing something rash.<br />
<br />
That morning the air was crisp and clean and the sky was just taking on a reddish hue that suggested a firey sunrise to come shortly as she made her way out of the temple and down the wide stone steps that led to the street in front of our guild. I hung back so as not to be seen ... I wasn't following her to pry into her business so much as I was curious to see why she had changed and to try to gain some insight into why one of our sect's greatest clerics was at such a quandry as to her very own future. The streets were nearly empty, save for the vendors setting their push carts up at the market and then a few more near the city gates. I slipped past the large Ogre and his assortment of pickled paladin and other such goods. It should be noted that Boomba has done time in the local jail for selling pickled lion and claiming it to be pickled dark elf ... the color was all wrong ... well he isn't too bright ... he is after all an Ogre. The guards gave barely a glace as she walked past them ... they did give me the once over as I made my way by ... but then probably decided that I was just a bit tardy and trying my best to catch up with my master.<br />
<br />
Velena walked slowly and made little effort to discearn if she were followed. That was a good thing as my armor is quite heavy and somewhat loud and I have none of the abilities of the rogue class. The only thing going for me in fact is that I am an elf and have a little bit of inanne dexterity ... a little bit. We walked through the East Commons and out into the plains of the West Commons .... through knee high grasses and between sparce trees. The path was easy and the sun not yet too hot so we came to the lake in a relatively short period of time, one after the other.<br />
<br />
Velena stapped by the shores and looked about and almost saw me ... I had grown careless and had almost stopped making any effort at all to stay hidden. So when she suddenly looked about I was nearly standing in the open. I jumped behind a tree and crouched in the grass ... grass hoppers danced about ... jumping off my vambraces and helm. When she settled down at the lake side I knealt by the tree and took off some of my gear. I laid my pack beside the tree and removed my gauntlets and helm. I set my hammer and footmans mace within easy reach and took a long draw from my canteen. The water was still cool and refreshing. Peering over the tall grasses I could see that my friend was in deep meditation ... I leaned back against the tree in a position so as to be able to arch my neck and see her as I needed. <br />
<br />
The sun grew hot and I guess I nodded off to sleep. It was in this dreamy state that I awoke with a start. The sound of a splash drew me back from the land of dreams. I nearly jumped up mace in hand ... then I remembered my task and crained my neck to see better. My friend had a sack in her hand and was dumping the contents into the water. I saw armor and weapons fall from the bag and finally she cast the fine leather itself onto the waters ... muttering "So be it". <br />
<br />
I was so shocked I fell back against the tree and was lost in thought for what was a very long time. When I again found myself ... and my reasoning ... it was dark, the birds were no longer singing and the stars were out. I sat there wondering what would become of us and our order. I thought about the things that I had heard said ... how the clerics were overlooked and under rated ... how we sat there and meditated while the tanks retrieved all the loot ... how in the old days when gems were taked they were given to the clerics to recoup their losses for spell reagents, I was growing poor buying gems and scrounging monies just to be able to go out and work at my chosen craft, I had never been given gems, they were always sold off and split ... how the warriors were always more worried about congradulating themselfves on a crit but were the first to grumble that we were taking too much time trying to be perfect and were wasting time setting up, things need to be right before we can hunt or wage war, otherwise people die, and that bothers me, they don't have to sleep at night worrying about weather a simple mistake on tomorrows field will cost someone's life, if they slip they mearly need to cast an eyebrow at me and know that I will cover for their mistake with a healing spell. I sat all through the night and thought about the way of the world and what had overcome it and sometime after that,  the moon was swallowed up by a passing cloud ... sleep finally came over me like a wave on a beach. <br />
<br />
I awoke to the sounds of birds squabbling. Someone had disturbed them. I stood up and looked about only to see my friend waste deep in water, thrashing about with a large pole. As I watched she hooked something with the pole and threw it up on the bank. My gaze followed the item ... spinning in air end over end ... till it crashed somewhat noisily into a small pile of wet gear. I walked slowly over to the edge of the bank by the pile of armor and such, and watched till she seemed to be done and then when she came out of the water I approached. <br />
<br />
She noticed me then and greeted me with the usual joyful flair that I had always known but something in her voice betrayed her uneasyness ... "Grimmond my friend, how are you" ... "and what brings you here to this lake on this particular morning ?"<br />
<br />
I told her that I had spent an uneasy night deep in thought about the passing of an age and had pondered my futre. As we cleaned and dried her gear, carefully removing all the weeds and muck, and put her armor back on ... taking care to make sure that none of the straps were damaged by their time at the bottom of the lake ... she explained to me what had come over her and the decision she had made to move on. But that with the sunset and this mornings sunrise she realised that life is a cycle and things change ... and we must change with it. We must be more assertive and speak up or with the next sunset there may be no more heros in need of our services. I grabbed my gear and followed her down the trail. She waited for me this time and we walked together, pausing at the inns to offer our services. <br />
<br />
A bard of just a few years staggered into the encampment badly mauled by a lion, and I rushed to his side, healing him and placing salves on his laserations, gradully he came around and after a time he looked to be nearly his old self again. Reaching into his bag he took out what must have been a weeks profits to him and offered them to me for my troubles ... I pushed them back and told him that I was here for him and his friends. The world needs more heros I explained and we walked off into the grass lands back towards Freeport. As I walked away it occured to me that I could change the world and I had just started to make that change.<br />
<br />
That night the sun set again and it rose the following morning like I am sure it always will.</font></p>
	
